Older adults often struggle with memory retrieval due to **less efficient memory organization**, making it harder to locate specific memories. While retrieval speed (I) and reduced long-term memory access (B) may also play a role, **disorganized memory structures** are a well-documented cognitive aging effect. The other options (e.g., intentional suppression, physical fatigue, or intentional quitting) lack strong empirical support.
